Skywave — live DSC monitor + ground-wave TDoA
=============================================

A browser-native view onto the routine maritime radio traffic almost
nobody reads anymore. Skywave picks dozens of public KiwiSDRs around
the world, tunes each to one of the six international Digital Selective
Calling channels (MF 2187.5 kHz and five HF frequencies), decodes every
burst, dedupes across receivers, and prints the result as a scrolling
table of who's calling whom, from where, about what.

For target regions where enough KiwiSDRs cluster around the same patch
of sea, Skywave also runs a TDOA solver: when ≥3 receivers hear the
same DSC burst, the cross-correlated arrival times triangulate the
transmitter's position to within tens of kilometres on MF.

How it works: one Cloudflare Durable Object per KiwiSDR channel holds
the only upstream WebSocket, runs the decoder at the edge, and fans
decoded calls out to every browser attached to it. One listener on
each channel, forever, serving everyone who turns up — regardless of
how many people land on the page. See `CLAUDE.md` for the design
narrative and `worker/src/` for the code.


Using it
--------

Open the page. The gateway composes a rack of KiwiSDRs covering the
relevant DSC channels for the selected region and the browser attaches
to each. The top-right dropdown narrows the scan:

* **ALL** — global rack (96 slots across 6 DSC bands).
* **ENGCH** — English Channel target cohort (35 MF receivers within
  400 km of (50°N, 0°E) — the methodology's best-case geometry, where
  TDOA fixes are reliably accurate within 50 km).
* **NAT, BSK, SEAP, PG** — long-baseline target cohorts for the North
  Atlantic, Black Sea, SE Asia / W Pacific, Persian Gulf. Useful for
  watching DSC traffic in those areas; TDOA fixes from these are
  multi-hop skywave and not as reliable.

Audio stays silent between transmissions. When a DSC FSK burst is
detected on one of the receivers we're listening to, the strongest
signal gets routed to your speakers — so you hear the actual tones of
the protocol the first time it happens, which is the fun bit.

Click a row to expand: decoder internals, the full list of receivers
that heard the call, and a mini-map showing where those receivers sit
along with the vessel's last known position. When TDOA solves a burst,
the fix is rendered as a circle on the map (radius = solver residual).

Vessel enrichment uses Global Fishing Watch's public search + tracks
endpoints, proxied through the Cloudflare Worker. Ship name, flag,
type, callsign, IMO and a decimated 14-day AIS track come back
automatically for every MMSI that GFW has data on. No API key needed.


Rack selection
--------------

Out of the ~900 public KiwiSDRs, the picker keeps the ones that are
worth listening to:

* **Active & reachable** — self-reports `status=active`, list entry
  refreshed within the last hour, doesn't IP-blacklist Cloudflare's
  egress ranges.
* **GPS-equipped & fixing** — TDOA needs per-frame GNSS timestamps
  for the shared time base (`fixes_hour ≥ 100`).
* **Coastal** (bbox picker only) — within 8° of a major port /
  chokepoint anchor. Target picks don't filter on coast; they
  already constrain by a centroid + radius.
* **Considerate** — ≥ 2 free user slots so a human listener always
  has one spare. Skywave never squats the last slot.

Cohort selection differs between bbox and target picks. Bbox uses
`freeSlots × coastalProximity × snrBonus × antennaBonus` greedy
across 6 DSC bands × ~16 slots each = 96 total. Target picks for
ground-wave-only regions take the closest receiver in each compass
octant, then top up with the next-closest unpicked, site-deduped at
5 km. Surround-mode targets (HF skywave) replicate one octant pick
across all 6 bands. See `CLAUDE.md` for the methodology in detail.


Etiquette
---------

Public KiwiSDR receivers have a limited number of user slots. The
Worker holds exactly one connection per channel per receiver —
`ident_user=skywave shared listener` — no matter how many humans are
viewing. A ReceiverDO tears itself down five minutes after the last
subscriber disconnects, so a quiet region stops squatting slots. The
≥ 2 free slots filter ensures we never take the last available slot.


Repo layout
-----------

    client/            static site (Pages / any HTTP server)
      index.html       entry point; Leaflet + JetBrains Mono + the app
      styles.css       the whole stylesheet, mobile-first
      app.js           v2 viewer: rack subscription, rendering, audio
      vessels.js       GFW vessel identity lookup
      regions.js       DSC channels, regional presets, MID→ISO
      map.js           per-card mini map (Leaflet)
      favicon.svg      Data Desk mark
    worker/            Cloudflare Worker + Durable Objects
      wrangler.toml    DO bindings + migrations
      src/
        index.js          router: /v2/rack, /v2/slot, /v2/tdoa/*, /gfw…
        directory-do.js   rack composer + receiver-list refresh
        receiver-do.js    per-channel KiwiSDR listener + decoder + fanout
        kiwi-upstream.js  server-side KiwiSDR WS client (IQ mode)
        dsc.js            ITU-R M.493 decoder
        regions.js        BANDS + bboxes + target regions + pickers
        tdoa.js           solver math: xcorr + solveTdoa (geodesic)
        tdoa-do.js        TDOADO: bucket → cross-correlate → solve
        location-hint.js  GPS → Cloudflare locationHint
    scripts/           offline validation + live testing
      test_tdoa.mjs            synthetic geometry — p50 ≈ 1.6 km
      test_tdoa_e2e.mjs        synthetic through coordinator — p50 ≈ 1.1 km
      tdoa_watch.mjs           live capture + GFW/LSEG ground truth
      analyse_solves.mjs       offline analyser for watch JSONL
      global_chokepoints.mjs   feasibility sweep — where can we run this?
      inject_tdoa*.mjs         synthetic injection at /v2/tdoa/inject


Local development
-----------------

The client is pure static ES modules; any HTTP server does it:

    cd client && python3 -m http.server 8000

The gateway needs wrangler:

    cd worker && npx wrangler dev
    # or: npx wrangler deploy

Point `index.html`'s `<meta name="skywave-gateway">` at your wrangler-
dev URL (e.g. `http://127.0.0.1:8787`) if you want local end-to-end.

Add `?debug=1` to the page URL for verbose console logging.

Run a live capture:

    node scripts/tdoa_watch.mjs --region english-channel --duration 1800 \
        --out /tmp/capture.jsonl --no-ais
    # then:
    node scripts/analyse_solves.mjs /tmp/capture.jsonl

Find new feasible target regions:

    node scripts/global_chokepoints.mjs


Credits & research
------------------

Decoder ported from the Data Desk research repo at
`~/Research/dsc-triangulation`. Original Python reference:
`scripts/dsc_decode_ddesk.py`. Canonical .NET reference:
`vendor/TAOSW.DSC_Decoder.Core/GMDSSDecoder.cs`. KiwiSDR practitioner
consensus on TDoA: HF Underground topic 117872 (ground-wave is what
actually works on the public fleet).
